 In this case, since we both chose R in the first round and earned 45$ each, it seems that my initial reasoning about reciprocity was correct. As I mentioned earlier, if either player consistently chooses the same option, they would receive 130$ while their opponent receives 136$.

In this situation, since we both chose R and got the maximum payoff of 45$, it is reasonable to assume that my opponent will also choose R in the next round. If I were to consistently reciprocate choices (R-R), we would earn a total of 135$ over the two rounds. Alternatively, if I change my strategy and pick B in the next round, my payoff would be 12$, while my opponent would receive 45$.

Given that we're playing for three rounds and considering the previous scenario where the other player might exploit me by choosing B every time, it seems more beneficial to stick with the reciprocity strategy. I would pick R again in this round. {R}
